The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Wednesday, April 28, 2004 				 Indo Gulf fourth quarter net dips
 OUR BUREAUX																								April 27: Indo Gulf Fertilisers today reported a 77.04 per cent drop in net profit at Rs 27.27 crore for the fourth quarter ended March 31, 2004 against Rs 118.79 crore registered a year earlier. Net sales stood at Rs 171.58 crore compared with Rs 290.33 crore in the year-ago period.																								The company reported a 47.76 per cent lower net profit for the year ended March at Rs 90.27 crore against Rs 172.80 crore posted in 2003. Net sales slipped to Rs 578.53 crore as against Rs 675.21 crore in 2002-03.																								The board of directors met today and recommended a dividend of Rs 2.80 per share.																								The financial performance for the current year is not comparable with the previous year due to higher subsidy arrears of Rs 132.96 crore in 2002-03 compared with last fiscal, managing director Rakesh Jain said. 																								Indo Gulf has applied to the government for brownfield expansion and was looking at overseas acquisitions, Jain said, adding the company would bid for Rashtriya Chemicals and Fertilisers as and when it is put up for divestment. ABB Q1 net zooms 																								Riding on the back of a robust power sector, ABB India has reported a net profit of Rs 16.9 crore for the first quarter ended March 31, 2004, up by 94 per cent compared with Rs 8.7 crore a year earlier. 																								The company reported revenues of Rs 448.9 crore, up by 55 per cent over Rs 290.2 crore during January to March 2003, ABB India vice-chairman and managing director Ravi Uppal said.Finolex Cables posts profit																								Finolex Cables Ltd has posted a 20 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 29.56 crore for the fiscal ended March 31, 2004 against Rs 24.72 crore in 2002-03. Total income for the reporting year rose by 10 per cent to Rs 568.9 crore (Rs 518.9 crore), said a company release.																								Net profit and total income for the fourth quarter ended March stood at Rs 3.36 crore (Rs 2.5 crore) and Rs 164 crore (Rs 158.6 crore) respectively, the release said.Bhel bottomline up																								Bharat Heavy Electricals Ltd today revised upwards its net profit for fiscal 2003-04 at Rs 635.50 crore, up 42.97 per cent against Rs 444.51 crore in the previous fiscal.																								The company had earlier announced a 38 per cent spurt in net profits during the year at Rs 615 crore. Net sales for the year increased by 14.63 per cent at Rs 8,844.46 crore against Rs 7,715.61 crore in 2002-03.																								Bhels net profit for the fourth quarter increased by 35.91 per cent to Rs 412.54 crore (Rs 303.55 crore). Net income rose by 13.38 per cent to Rs 3,980.82 crore (Rs 3,510.94 crore). Exim Bank net rises																								Export and Import Bank of India has posted an 11 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 229 crore for the fiscal ended March 2004 against Rs 207 crore a year earlier. It would pay a dividend of Rs 47 crore for 2003-04 to the Centre, chairman and managing director T. C. Venkat Subramanian said. 
